Addressing the problem requires a multifaceted strategy. First, education systems should embed inclusive science curricula from an early age, using role models that reflect diverse genders. In my own experience as a retail worker in Bologna, I saw how children’s curiosity can be nurtured when teachers speak about scientists of all backgrounds; this small shift can dismantle stereotypes before they take root. Second, funding agencies must adopt blind review processes and actively encourage proposals from underrepresented groups. The National Science Foundation’s recent “Women in STEM” grant program is a step in the right direction, but it needs to be expanded with transparent metrics on success rates. Third, workplaces should implement flexible scheduling, parental leave policies that are not gender‑biased, and mentorship programs that pair junior scientists with senior mentors regardless of gender. In my own community, I’ve observed that when a senior scientist volunteers as a mentor, the mentee’s confidence skyrockets; this personal touch can counteract systemic biases.

